div.h2: TLB Flush Decision Tree invlpg vs Full CR3 Reload
div.p: Start: a page table entry has been modified
Reason: No stale TLB entry exists for this virtual address it was never cached (present=0 previously). Cost: 0 cycles (skip flush entirely)

text.tspan: (loading a new page directory into CR3)?

div.p: x86 instruction: INVLPG m Evicts exactly one TLB entry for the given virtual address. Cost: ~2050 cycles (~10 ns @ 3 GHz) Effect: O(1) constant time regardless of TLB size or occupancy. When: Permission change, frame remap, or presentnot-present for a single page.

Cost: N ~2050 cycles where N = number of modified PTEs. Preferred over full CR3 reload when N < ~32 (avoids thrashing hot kernel TLB entries shared by all processes). If N is large (e.g., unmapping a 1 GB region), full CR3 reload becomes cheaper.

text.tspan: (write new PD physical addr to CR3)

div.p: Assembly: mov cr3, <new_pd_phys> Flushes ALL non-global TLB entries. Global entries (PTE_GLOBAL set) survive. Cost: ~200500 cycles (~100 ns)

ul.li: burst of TLB cold-misses afterward for kernel pages not marked GLOBAL. When: Context switch between processes with different page directories.

text.tspan: Is the modified kernel mapping shared
Full CR3 Reload in current process

div.p: Assembly: mov eax, cr3; mov cr3, eax Reloads same physical PD address flushes all non-global entries in the CURRENT CPU's TLB. Cost: ~200500 cycles When: Kernel page table changed (e.g., kmalloc heap extends, new kernel mapping added/removed).

On multicore systems, each CPU has its own private TLB. Modifying a shared kernel PTE on CPU 0 leaves stale entries on CPU 1, 2, N. Required action: Send an Inter-Processor Interrupt (IPI) to all other CPUs, instructing them to execute invlpg or CR3 reload. Must wait for all CPUs to ACK before the modifying CPU can proceed. Cost: microseconds (IPI round-trip) This is why munmap is expensive in production Linux on many-core systems. M1M4 kernel: single-core only. No IPI implementation required.
Legend No action needed invlpg targeted, cheap CR3 reload full flush, costly SMP future IPI required
